ly because of the varying vocalization, and also because this root is underdeveloped or it has the unrelated meaning of a “bowl”. The Aramaic might in turn come from Akkadian 𒅔𒉡𒁕 (/⁠tibnu⁠/, “straw”) but can likewise be cognate. Else the word is only present in Hebrew תֶּבֶן (teḇen, “straw”), in which language there is nothing to relate to either.\n\nDenominal verb of تِبْن (tibn, “straw”). In the “to bung” sense allegedly motivated by Spanish taponar.\n\nUncertain with possible connection to Akkadian 𒋰𒉌𒌈 (/⁠tabnītu⁠/, “an offering basket, a place to deposit tribute to a ruler or offerings before deities”, literally “well-arranged, well-made or constructed”) and Akkadian 𒁀𒀀𒉡 (/⁠bānu⁠/, “a ewer, vessel that fills up other vessels”, literally “that which does what it was made for; a by-name for a ewer in ritual texts”), therefore distantly being connected to ب ن ي (b n y).\n\nLike the more productive root ط ب ن (ṭ b n), from which there is with the like meanings طَبِنَ (ṭabina) and طَبِن (ṭabin)."}, "ipa": null, "lanes_definition": {"source": "lanes", "entries": [{"entry_id": "n3765", "headword_ar": "تِبْنٌ", "root": "tbn", "body": [{"kind": "text", "text": "(S, M, Msb, K, &c.) and ↓"}, {"kind": "arabic", "text_bw": "tabonN", "text_ar": "تَبْنٌ", "orth_type": "arrow"}, {"kind": "text", "text": "(M, K)"}, {"kind": "italic_en", "text": "Straw;"}, {"kind": "text", "text": "i. e. the"}, {"kind": "italic_en", "text": "stalks,"}, {"kind": "text", "text": "or"}, {"kind": "italic_en", "text": "stems,"}, {"kind": "text", "text": "("}, {"kind": "arabic", "text_bw": "EaSiyf", "text_ar": "عَصِيف"}, {"kind": "text", "text": ", M, K,) or the"}, {"kind": "italic_en", "text": "stalk,"}, {"kind": "text", "text": "or"}, {"kind": "italic_en", "text": "stem,"}, {"kind": "text", "text": "("}, {"kind": "arabic", "text_bw": "saAq", "text_ar": "سَاق"}, {"kind": "text", "text": ", Msb,)"}, {"kind": "italic_en", "text": "of seed-produce,"}, {"kind": "text", "text": "(M, Msb, K,)"}, {"kind": "i